1
00:00:08,543 --> 00:00:11,163
Hello, my name is Willy Benz

2
00:00:11,163 --> 00:00:16,424
I'm a professor for astrophysics
and physics at the University of Bern

3
00:00:16,424 --> 00:00:18,114
in Switzerland.

4
00:00:18,114 --> 00:00:23,897
I did my physics studies in Neuchâtel
and Geneva where I got my degree.

5
00:00:23,897 --> 00:00:29,094
Then I spent some time in the USA
at Los Alamos, at Harvard

6
00:00:29,094 --> 00:00:32,701
and at the University of Arizona
before coming back

7
00:00:32,701 --> 00:00:39,218
to the University of Bern
where I'm working since 1997.

8
00:00:39,218 --> 00:00:43,855
My research interests deal 
with planetary science,

9
00:00:43,855 --> 00:00:48,847
in particular, the formation
and the evolution of planetary systems

10
00:00:48,847 --> 00:00:53,718
and planets and small bodies
in the solar system as well as outside

11
00:00:54,343 --> 00:00:57,077
in relation with exoplanets.

12
00:01:07,850 --> 00:01:15,221
CHEOPS is the first small mission
in ESA, the European Space Agency

13
00:01:16,051 --> 00:01:17,671
Science Program.

14
00:01:17,671 --> 00:01:22,534
And it's something very special
because it's the first of its kind,

15
00:01:22,534 --> 00:01:26,898
and it has a bit different constraints 
then all the other missions

16
00:01:26,898 --> 00:01:29,935
that are not normally run by ESA.

17
00:01:29,935 --> 00:01:33,674
In particular, as the name says,
it's a small mission.

18
00:01:33,674 --> 00:01:41,359
And small means budget wise 
so we have been limited in the budget.

19
00:01:41,359 --> 00:01:46,969
ESA contribution to CHEOPS 
is 50 million euros,

20
00:01:46,969 --> 00:01:52,082
and we also have limited time
at our disposal to build

21
00:01:52,082 --> 00:01:55,189
and fly the mission, the
constraint was 4 years

22
00:01:55,189 --> 00:01:56,549
of development time.

23
00:01:56,549 --> 00:02:03,755
So the challenges with the small missions
were to propose a scientific mission

24
00:02:03,755 --> 00:02:09,116
that could be relatively cheap
and at the same time be executed

25
00:02:09,116 --> 00:02:11,047
relatively fast.

26
00:02:11,047 --> 00:02:14,905
And so we proposed the idea 
of a follow up mission

27
00:02:14,905 --> 00:02:18,968
to characterize exoplanets.

28
00:02:18,968 --> 00:02:25,305
So the idea is we know a lot
of planets from radial velocities,

29
00:02:25,305 --> 00:02:29,265
where we measure the wobble 
of the star,

30
00:02:29,265 --> 00:02:33,897
and for these planets we know 
at least a lower limit of the mass

31
00:02:33,897 --> 00:02:36,888
besides orbital parameters.

32
00:02:36,888 --> 00:02:39,407
On the other hand, 
we know a lot of planets

33
00:02:39,407 --> 00:02:43,907
from transit measurements
where satellites have measured the radius

34
00:02:43,907 --> 00:02:47,798
of these planets by looking
at the dimming of the light

35
00:02:47,798 --> 00:02:51,193
when the planet transits 
in front of its star.

36
00:02:51,864 --> 00:02:57,434
However, we have very few objects
for which we know both the mass

37
00:02:57,434 --> 00:02:58,775
and the radius.

38
00:02:58,775 --> 00:03:02,520
So the idea with CHEOPS
was to follow the brightest stars

39
00:03:02,520 --> 00:03:06,694
for which we know their planets
and try to find a transit there

40
00:03:06,694 --> 00:03:09,919
in order to measure their radius.

41
00:03:09,919 --> 00:03:13,163
So it is a follow-up mission,
it's not a discovery mission,

42
00:03:13,163 --> 00:03:17,815
but it will allow us to measure
with high precision

43
00:03:17,815 --> 00:03:21,931
a large number, we hope,
of exoplanets.

44
00:03:26,918 --> 00:03:32,290
So, of course, during this 4 ½ years
of development, they are a number

45
00:03:32,290 --> 00:03:35,804
of key elements that have 
to fall into place.

46
00:03:35,804 --> 00:03:41,858
First, of course, was the selection itself
when we got selected,

47
00:03:41,858 --> 00:03:48,649
and that was in 2012
when CHEOPS was selected by ESA.

48
00:03:48,649 --> 00:03:55,960
And then, as usual, in the ESA missions,
there is a detailed study phase

49
00:03:55,960 --> 00:04:03,300
where selected missions are being studied
in order to see whether the mission

50
00:04:03,300 --> 00:04:09,324
can actually fulfill 
its scientific promise within budget

51
00:04:09,324 --> 00:04:12,048
and within time scale.

52
00:04:12,048 --> 00:04:18,160
And we managed to get through this study,
and we were, what ESA calls, adopted,

53
00:04:18,160 --> 00:04:19,740
mission adoption.

54
00:04:20,066 --> 00:04:26,346
About a year later, since then, 
we've been building models,

55
00:04:26,346 --> 00:04:34,913
and right now, in spring of 2016,
we're going through CDR,

56
00:04:34,913 --> 00:04:38,459
the Critical Design Review,
where everything has to fit.

57
00:04:38,459 --> 00:04:41,196
All the models, all the tests 
have been made.

58
00:04:41,196 --> 00:04:44,140
All the breadboards
have been completed,

59
00:04:44,140 --> 00:04:49,611
and the final review 
before the actual building

60
00:04:49,611 --> 00:04:55,535
of the satellite in industry
and delivery for launch.

61
00:04:55,535 --> 00:05:03,407
Launch-readiness is foreseen
end of 2017.

62
00:05:03,407 --> 00:05:09,786
CHEOPS will be a passenger 
on a rocket with a much bigger satellite

63
00:05:09,793 --> 00:05:13,058
to minimize the cost,
and because of that,

64
00:05:13,058 --> 00:05:19,094
the launch date will depend 
on what the main passenger will do.

65
00:05:19,094 --> 00:05:21,732
And so we just have 
a launch-readiness date,

66
00:05:21,732 --> 00:05:26,570
but this will be the big date,
end of '17,

67
00:05:26,570 --> 00:05:29,553
and then whenever the launch
will take place will probably

68
00:05:29,553 --> 00:05:35,907
be very early 2018, with a nominal
mission duration of 3 ½ years.

69
00:05:40,687 --> 00:05:44,181
On CHEOPs, I am what's called
the principle investigator,

70
00:05:44,181 --> 00:05:50,641
so basically I'm in charge
of organizing the team

71
00:05:50,641 --> 00:05:56,766
that builds this satellite,
I should say, the instrument.

72
00:05:56,766 --> 00:05:59,130
There are two different aspects
of this mission.

73
00:05:59,130 --> 00:06:03,493
ESA is responsible for launch facilities.

74
00:06:03,493 --> 00:06:07,291
It's responsible for the platform
and the consortium,

75
00:06:07,291 --> 00:06:11,556
which is 11 European countries
working together,

76
00:06:11,556 --> 00:06:14,477
is responsible
for delivering the payload.

77
00:06:14,477 --> 00:06:18,544
In our case, the payload
of CHEOPS is a simple telescope

78
00:06:18,960 --> 00:06:22,228
that is mounted on the platform.

79
00:06:22,228 --> 00:06:25,295
The telescope is able to point
to different stars

80
00:06:25,295 --> 00:06:28,857
that we want to study the planets.

81
00:06:28,857 --> 00:06:36,664
So my role is to run this consortium
of 11 countries, make sure

82
00:06:36,664 --> 00:06:43,304
all this runs smoothly
and try to intervene

83
00:06:43,304 --> 00:06:47,557
whenever this is the case;
it's necessary.

84
00:06:47,557 --> 00:06:54,478
In Bern, we have a so-called prime
of the instrument,

85
00:06:54,478 --> 00:06:58,541
and therefore, the instrument 
is being designed.

86
00:06:58,541 --> 00:07:04,092
It will be assembled when all the pieces
come from the different countries.

87
00:07:04,092 --> 00:07:07,878
It will be assembled in Bern 
and then it will be calibrated

88
00:07:07,878 --> 00:07:09,391
and tested.

89
00:07:09,391 --> 00:07:13,206
All that in Bern before being shipped 
to the platform.

90
00:07:20,238 --> 00:07:22,250
Well that it is for sure a challenge.

91
00:07:22,250 --> 00:07:28,839
I mean from an organization
