99
00:08:03,315 --> 00:08:05,637
then we have major problems.

100
00:08:05,637 --> 00:08:11,259
So it is an enormous amount of work
to define all the interfaces

101
00:08:11,259 --> 00:08:16,485
between the different parts
of the instrument that are delivered

102
00:08:16,485 --> 00:08:18,397
from different countries.

103
00:08:18,397 --> 00:08:23,972
Now the good part of such a collaboration
is it makes things possible.

104
00:08:23,972 --> 00:08:29,681
We alone, Switzerland alone, Bern alone
would never have had the means

105
00:08:29,681 --> 00:08:33,694
to build the entire payload alone.

106
00:08:33,694 --> 00:08:38,808
So grouping ourselves, getting together,
creating such a consortium,

107
00:08:38,808 --> 00:08:45,153
allows the building of CHEOPS,
allows to get the funding together

108
00:08:45,153 --> 00:08:49,019
to be able to build this,
allows us to get the experience

109
00:08:49,019 --> 00:08:53,440
and know-how together
in order to build a working instrument.

110
00:08:53,440 --> 00:09:01,433
It is an administrative overhead
quite large, but it is the only way

111
00:09:01,433 --> 00:09:08,279
that one can get to actually do 
these relatively complex

112
00:09:08,279 --> 00:09:11,475
and expensive hardware.

113
00:09:11,475 --> 00:09:17,165
And it's interesting to work 
with people from different countries.

114
00:09:17,165 --> 00:09:20,896
You first of all get to visit 
the different labs,

115
00:09:20,896 --> 00:09:22,723
which is always interesting.

116
00:09:22,723 --> 00:09:27,076
You get to meet the different culture,
eat the different food.

117
00:09:27,076 --> 00:09:31,988
So it has an interesting 
cultural experience to it.

118
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:34,984
But I must say sometimes,
it would be easier if we were

119
00:09:34,984 --> 00:09:37,409
to do everything inhouse.

120
00:09:43,759 --> 00:09:51,010
So CHEOPS needs to be measuring 
the radii of exoplanets.

121
00:09:51,010 --> 00:09:55,165
In particular, also small ones, 
an object like the Earth.

122
00:09:55,165 --> 00:09:59,696
Now if you take the Earth,
and if you have the Earth's transit

123
00:09:59,696 --> 00:10:03,091
in front of the Sun,
and you look at the Sun

124
00:10:03,091 --> 00:10:07,674
from far away, you will see 
a slight decrease of the luminosity

125
00:10:07,674 --> 00:10:11,792
of the Sun when the planet transits,
and this slight decrease

126
00:10:11,792 --> 00:10:17,194
is roughly one part in 10^4
or 100 ppm.

127
00:10:17,194 --> 00:10:23,118
So it is a minute decrease 
in the light intensity from the star

128
00:10:23,118 --> 00:10:25,401
that we have to measure.

129
00:10:25,401 --> 00:10:28,450
First of all, this is why we cannot 
do it from the ground,

130
00:10:28,450 --> 00:10:33,235
so this is why we have to go to space
because the atmosphere has introduced

131
00:10:33,235 --> 00:10:37,433
too much noise in the light signals,
so we cannot do it from the ground,

132
00:10:37,433 --> 00:10:39,660
at such a small planet.

133
00:10:39,660 --> 00:10:46,735
So in space is the only way to measure 
photometrically such signal

134
00:10:46,735 --> 00:10:51,095
with precision that allows us
to measure these radii in the end.

135
00:10:51,095 --> 00:10:54,637
You have to imagine the transit 
takes several hours.

136
00:10:54,637 --> 00:10:58,762
The planet transits during several hours 
in front of the star.

137
00:10:58,762 --> 00:11:03,823
During this time, the satellite 
orbits the Earth several times,

138
00:11:03,823 --> 00:11:08,741
and the result we have to measure 
the light over this period

139
00:11:08,741 --> 00:11:12,622
to a precision better
than these 100 ppm

140
00:11:12,622 --> 00:11:15,112
if you want to measure the radius 
with accuracy.

141
00:11:15,112 --> 00:11:18,387
So we set the requirement at 20 ppm.

142
00:11:18,387 --> 00:11:23,450
So we want to be able to measure 
the light signal during a period

143
00:11:23,450 --> 00:11:27,759
of several hours to a precision of 20 ppm.

144
00:11:27,759 --> 00:11:33,309
And this is a real challenge because 
the satellite is in a Low Earth Orbit,

145
00:11:33,309 --> 00:11:36,457
orbiting the Earth, 
so you have reflected lights

146
00:11:36,457 --> 00:11:38,413
from the surface of the Earth.

147
00:11:38,413 --> 00:11:41,527
You have reflected light 
from the surface of the Moon.

148
00:11:41,527 --> 00:11:43,906
You have the satellite orbiting.

149
00:11:43,906 --> 00:11:47,965
The satellite is partly in the sun,
partly in the shade.

150
00:11:47,965 --> 00:11:52,627
You have terrific temperature gradients
across the structure,

151
00:11:52,627 --> 00:11:57,378
and all that is a real challenge 
to measure the precision.

152
00:11:57,378 --> 00:12:02,510
The rest is relatively, I should say,
relatively simple for what space

153
00:12:02,510 --> 00:12:03,838
is concerned.

154
00:12:03,838 --> 00:12:07,987
The real challenge is to measure
this light's signal to that precision

155
00:12:07,987 --> 00:12:10,346
over these periods of time.

156
00:12:10,346 --> 00:12:13,647
And this is a necessity 
because if we do not make it

157
00:12:13,647 --> 00:12:17,309
to that precision, you cannot 
measure the radius of the planet

158
00:12:17,309 --> 00:12:18,733
without precision.

159
00:12:18,733 --> 00:12:22,161
And the purpose of measuring the radius
together with its mass

160
00:12:22,161 --> 00:12:27,003
is to have the mean density of the planet 
in order to determine

161
00:12:27,003 --> 00:12:28,552
what this planet is made of.

162
00:12:28,552 --> 00:12:30,698
Is is a ball of gas?
Is it a ball of rock?

163
00:12:30,698 --> 00:12:34,953
Is it a mixture of both?
Does it have water and so on?

164
00:12:34,953 --> 00:12:39,363
This you can say something
if you can measure the mean density

165
00:12:39,363 --> 00:12:43,014
with enough precision, 
that is the mass and the radius

166
00:12:43,014 --> 00:12:45,049
with enough precision.

167
00:12:45,049 --> 00:12:52,549
So all the scientific, technical challenge
for CHEOPS resides in being able

168
00:12:52,549 --> 00:12:56,020
to measure the signal to that precision.

169
00:12:56,020 --> 00:13:02,262
So all sorts of technical 
development exist, baffle, inner baffle.

170
00:13:02,262 --> 00:13:07,508
All sorts of control of the system
have been built in to achieve

171
00:13:07,508 --> 00:13:09,527
this precision.

172
00:13:09,941 --> 00:13:17,438
The second and third challenges
have to do with specificity of S-missions [Small-missions]

173
00:13:17,438 --> 00:13:23,088
in the fact that we have to build it 
within a financial envelope

174
00:13:23,088 --> 00:13:27,042
for ESA of 50 million
and within 4 ½ years.

175
00:13:27,042 --> 00:13:31,676
And this means enormous stress
on the time scale.

176
00:13:31,676 --> 00:13:33,396
Things have to proceed fast.

177
00:13:33,396 --> 00:13:36,242
There is no time 
to study things at length.

178
00:13:36,242 --> 00:13:39,270
Things have to be decided, studied fast,

179
00:13:39,270 --> 00:13:43,869
and there is no time to try out things
because, again, the time is

180
00:13:43,869 --> 00:13:48,215
of the essence,
and we have to use almost

181
00:13:48,215 --> 00:13:53,021
off-the-shelf components
because there is no time to develop

182
00:13:53,021 --> 00:13:54,606
new technology.

183
00:13:54,606 --> 00:13:58,451
So all this makes it 
a real challenge actually.

184
00:14:03,578 --> 00:14:06,877
CHEOPS is not a discovery telescope.

185
00:14:06,877 --> 00:14:13,571
Most all of the other telescopes 
that have been flown in missions

186
00:14:13,571 --> 00:14:17,092
that have been flown so far
dealing with exoplanets,

187
00:14:17,092 --> 00:14:21,174
namely CoRoT, Kepler,
in the future, TESS.

188
00:14:21,174 --> 00:14:26,601
Those are all missions aimed 
at discovering exoplanets.

189
00:14:26,601 --> 00:14:30,391
In other words, these telescopes
look at the patch in the sky

190
00:14:30,391 --> 00:14:34,730
for a certain number of time,
monitor the luminosity

191
00:14:34,730 --> 00:14:37,659
of individual stars 
during this amount of time

192
00:14:37,659 --> 00:14:42,033
and detect those for which 
a slight decrease of intensity

193
00:14:42,033 --> 00:14:46,443
can be the cause of a transiting planet.

194
00:14:46,443 --> 00:14:48,076
CHEOPS is different.

195
00:14:48,076 --> 00:14:50,307
CHEOPS doesn't look 
at the patch of the sky,

196
00:14:50,307 --> 00:14:52,553
doesn't look at 100,000 stars 
at the same time.

197
00:14:52,553 --> 00:14:56,286
CHEOPS looks 
at a single star at a time.

198
00:14:56,286 --> 00:14:59,530
So you have to know where to look.

199
00:14:59,530 --> 00:15:03,350
So we are looking at stars 
that we know have planets,

200
00:15:03,350 --> 00:15:06,443
and with CHEOPS we're going to see
if the planet transits.

201
00:15:06,443 --> 00:15:11,575
In other words, if the planet 
is in the right geometrical orientation

202
00:15:11,575 --> 00:15:16,694
so that its orbital trajectory
takes it along the line of sight

203
00:15:16,694 --> 00:15:18,511
through the line of sight.

204
00:15:18,511 --> 00:15:24,655
So in that sense, CHEOPS is unique
in this kind of satellite,

205
00:15:24,655 --> 00:15:28,248
in a sense that it is really 
a follow-up mission

206
00:15:28,248 --> 00:15:30,669
and not a discovery mission.

207
00:15:30,669 --> 00:15:32,569
So you can choose your targets.

208
00:15:32,569 --> 00:15:34,786
You can move your telescope
in the sky.

209
00:15:34,786 --> 00:15:39,260
You can look anywhere 
in the sky pretty much,

210
00:15:39,260 --> 00:15:44,887
not completely,
and follow individual objects

211
00:15:44,887 --> 00:15:45,916
at a time,

212
00:15:45,916 --> 00:15:49,132
what none of the others 
have been able to do.

213
00:15:49,132 --> 00:15:52,431
So on one hand, 
we lose the aspect of discovery.

214
00:15:52,431 --> 00:15:56,598
On the other hand, 
we gain extraordinary flexibility

215
00:15:56,598 --> 00:16:00,290
because we can point at any target 
that interests us.

216
00:16:13,338 --> 00:16:19,947
So, indeed, the observing time,
the 3 ½ year observing time

217
00:16:19,947 --> 00:16:24,466
from CHEOPS which correspond
